        "type": "tool_result",
        "content": "1\t# Django - Docs\n2\t\n3\tPostHog makes it easy to get data about traffic and usage of your Django app. Integrating PostHog enables analytics, custom events capture, feature flags, error tracking, and more.\n4\t\n5\tThis guide walks you through integrating PostHog into your Django app using the [Python SDK](/docs/libraries/python.md).\n6\t\n7\t## Beta: integration via LLM\n8\t\n9\tInstall PostHog for Django in seconds with our wizard by running this prompt with [LLM coding agents](/blog/envoy-wizard-llm-agent.md) like Cursor and Bolt, or by running it in your terminal.\n10\t\n11\t`npx @posthog/wizard@latest`\n12\t\n13\t[Learn more](/wizard.md)\n14\t\n15\tOr, to integrate manually, continue with the rest of this guide.\n16\t\n17\t## Installation\n18\t\n19\tTo start, run `pip install posthog` to install PostHog’s Python SDK.\n20\t\n21\t> **Note:** Version `7.x` of the PostHog Python SDK requires Python 3.10 or higher.\n22\t\n23\tThen, configure PostHog in your app config so it's initialized when Django starts:\n24\t\n25\tyour\\_app/apps.py\n26\t\n27\tPostHog AI\n28\t\n29\t```python\n30\tfrom django.apps import AppConfig\n31\timport posthog\n32\tclass YourAppConfig(AppConfig):\n33\t    name = 'your_app_name'\n34\t    def ready(self):\n35\t        posthog.api_key = '<ph_project_token>'\n36\t        posthog.host = 'https://us.i.posthog.com'\n37\t```\n38\t\n39\tNext, if you haven't done so already, add your `AppConfig` to `INSTALLED_APPS` in `settings.py`:\n40\t\n41\tsettings.py\n42\t\n43\tPostHog AI\n44\t\n45\t```python\n46\tINSTALLED_APPS = [\n47\t    # ... other apps\n48\t    'your_app_name.apps.YourAppConfig',\n49\t]\n50\t```\n51\t\n52\tYou can find your project token and instance address in [your project settings](https://app.posthog.com/project/settings).\n53\t\n54\tTo capture events from any file, import `posthog` and call the method you need. For example:\n55\t\n56\tPython\n57\t\n58\tPostHog AI\n59\t\n60\t```python\n61\timport posthog\n62\tfrom posthog import identify_context\n63\tdef some_request(request):\n64\t    with posthog.new_context():\n65\t        # Django includes request.user for anonymous visitors too. Only identify\n66\t        # the context when the visitor is logged in.\n67\t        if request.user.is_authenticated:\n68\t            identify_context(str(request.user.pk))\n69\t        posthog.capture('event_name')\n70\t```\n71\t\n72\tEvents captured without a context or explicit `distinct_id` are sent as [anonymous events](/docs/data/anonymous-vs-identified-events.md) with an auto-generated `distinct_id`. See the [Python SDK docs](/docs/libraries/python.md#person-profiles-and-properties) for more details.\n73\t\n74\t## Identifying users\n75\t\n76\t> **Identifying users is required.** Backend events need a `distinct_id` that matches the ID your frontend uses when calling `posthog.identify()`. Without this, backend events are orphaned — they can't be linked to frontend event captures, [session replays](/docs/session-replay.md), [LLM traces](/docs/ai-engineering.md), or [error tracking](/docs/error-tracking.md).\n77\t>\n78\t> See our guide on [identifying users](/docs/getting-started/identify-users.md) for how to set this up.\n79\t\n80\t## Django contexts middleware\n81\t\n82\tThe Python SDK provides a Django middleware that automatically wraps all requests with a [context](/docs/libraries/python.md#contexts). This middleware extracts session and user information from each request and tags all events captured during that request with relevant metadata.\n83\t\n84\t### Basic setup\n85\t\n86\tAdd the middleware to your Django settings. If your app uses Django authentication, place it after `django.contrib.auth.middleware.AuthenticationMiddleware` so the middleware can use the authenticated Django user as a distinct ID fallback and capture the user's email.\n87\t\n88\tPython\n89\t\n90\tPostHog AI\n91\t\n92\t```python\n93\tMIDDLEWARE = [\n94\t    # ... other middleware\n95\t    'posthog.integrations.django.PosthogContextMiddleware',\n96\t    # ... other middleware\n97\t]\n98\t```\n99\t\n100\tThe middleware uses the globally configured `posthog` client by default, so you don't need to create or pass it a separate client instance.\n101\t\n102\tThe middleware automatically extracts and uses:\n103\t\n104\t-   **Session ID** from the `X-POSTHOG-SESSION-ID` header, if present\n105\t-   **Distinct ID** from the `X-POSTHOG-DISTINCT-ID` header, if present, falling back to the authenticated Django user's `pk` (Django's primary-key alias, which works with custom user models)\n106\t-   **User email** from the authenticated Django user's `email` as `email`\n107\t-   **Current URL** as `$current_url`\n108\t-   **Request method** as `$request_method`\n109\t-   **Request path** as `$request_path`\n110\t-   **Forwarded IP address** from `X-Forwarded-For` as `$ip`\n111\t-   **User agent** from `User-Agent` as `$user_agent`\n112\t\n113\tThe session and distinct ID headers are sanitized before use. Empty values are ignored, control characters are removed, values are trimmed, and values are capped at 1000 characters.\n114\t\n115\tAll events captured during the request (including exceptions) include these properties and are associated with the extracted session and distinct ID.\n116\t\n117\tIf you're using [PostHog JS](/docs/libraries/js.md) on the frontend, configure [`tracing_headers`](/docs/libraries/js/config.md#tracing-headers) for your Django backend hostname so browser requests include the session and distinct ID headers.\n118\t\n119\t### Exception capture\n120\t\n121\tBy default, the middleware captures exceptions and sends them to PostHog's error tracking using the globally configured `posthog` client. This includes Django view exceptions that Django converts into error responses.\n122\t\n123\tDisable this by setting:\n124\t\n125\tPython\n126\t\n127\tPostHog AI\n128\t\n129\t```python\n130\t# settings.py\n131\tPOSTHOG_MW_CAPTURE_EXCEPTIONS = False\n132\t```\n133\t\n134\t### Adding custom tags\n135\t\n136\tUse `POSTHOG_MW_EXTRA_TAGS` to add custom properties to all requests:\n137\t\n138\tPython\n139\t\n140\tPostHog AI\n141\t\n142\t```python\n143\t# settings.py\n144\tdef add_user_tags(request):\n145\t    # type: (HttpRequest) -> Dict[str, Any]\n146\t    tags = {}\n147\t    if hasattr(request, 'user') and request.user.is_authenticated:\n148\t        # Use pk instead of id so this works with custom User primary keys.\n149\t        tags['user_id'] = str(request.user.pk)\n150\t        tags['email'] = request.user.email\n151\t    return tags\n152\tPOSTHOG_MW_EXTRA_TAGS = add_user_tags\n153\t```\n154\t\n155\t#### Filtering requests\n156\t\n157\tSkip tracking for certain requests using `POSTHOG_MW_REQUEST_FILTER`:\n158\t\n159\tPython\n160\t\n161\tPostHog AI\n162\t\n163\t```python\n164\t# settings.py\n165\tdef should_track_request(request):\n166\t    # type: (HttpRequest) -> bool\n167\t    # Don't track health checks or admin requests\n168\t    if request.path.startswith('/health') or request.path.startswith('/admin'):\n169\t        return False\n170\t    return True\n171\tPOSTHOG_MW_REQUEST_FILTER = should_track_request\n172\t```\n173\t\n174\t### Modifying default tags\n175\t\n176\tUse `POSTHOG_MW_TAG_MAP` to modify or remove default tags:\n177\t\n178\tPython\n179\t\n180\tPostHog AI\n181\t\n182\t```python\n183\t# settings.py\n184\tdef customize_tags(tags):\n185\t    # type: (Dict[str, Any]) -> Dict[str, Any]\n186\t    # Remove URL for privacy\n187\t    tags.pop('$current_url', None)\n188\t    # Add custom prefix to method\n189\t    if '$request_method' in tags:\n190\t        tags['http_method'] = tags.pop('$request_method')\n191\t    return tags\n192\tPOSTHOG_MW_TAG_MAP = customize_tags\n193\t```\n194\t\n195\t### Complete configuration example\n196\t\n197\tPython\n198\t\n199\tPostHog AI\n200\t\n201\t```python\n202\t# settings.py\n203\tdef add_request_context(request):\n204\t    # type: (HttpRequest) -> Dict[str, Any]\n205\t    tags = {}\n206\t    if hasattr(request, 'user') and request.user.is_authenticated:\n207\t        tags['user_type'] = 'authenticated'\n208\t        # Use pk instead of id so this works with custom User primary keys.\n209\t        tags['user_id'] = str(request.user.pk)\n210\t    else:\n211\t        tags['user_type'] = 'anonymous'\n212\t    # Add request info\n213\t    tags['user_agent'] = request.META.get('HTTP_USER_AGENT', '')\n214\t    return tags\n215\tdef filter_tracking(request):\n216\t    # type: (HttpRequest) -> bool\n217\t    # Skip internal endpoints\n218\t    return not request.path.startswith(('/health', '/metrics', '/admin'))\n219\tdef clean_tags(tags):\n220\t    # type: (Dict[str, Any]) -> Dict[str, Any]\n221\t    # Remove sensitive data\n222\t    tags.pop('user_agent', None)\n223\t    return tags\n224\tPOSTHOG_MW_EXTRA_TAGS = add_request_context\n225\tPOSTHOG_MW_REQUEST_FILTER = filter_tracking\n226\tPOSTHOG_MW_TAG_MAP = clean_tags\n227\tPOSTHOG_MW_CAPTURE_EXCEPTIONS = True\n228\t```\n229\t\n230\tAll events captured within the request context automatically include the configured tags and are associated with the session and user identified from the request headers or Django authentication.\n231\t\n232\tThe middleware supports both sync (WSGI) and async (ASGI) Django applications. In async mode, it uses Django's `request.auser()` API when available to avoid synchronous user access.\n233\t\n234\t## Next steps\n235\t\n236\tFor any technical questions for how to integrate specific PostHog features into Django (such as analytics, feature flags, A/B testing, etc.), have a look at our [Python SDK docs](/docs/libraries/python.md).\n237\t\n238\tAlternatively, the following tutorials can help you get started:\n239\t\n240\t-   [Setting up Django analytics, feature flags, and more](/tutorials/django-analytics.md)\n241\t-   [How to set up A/B tests in Django](/tutorials/django-ab-tests.md)\n242\t\n243\t### Community questions\n244\t\n245\tAsk a question\n246\t\n247\t### Was this page useful?\n248\t\n249\tHelpfulCould be better"
