[2026-07-03T01:58:59.495Z] SDK Message: user {
  "type": "user",
  "message": {
    "role": "user",
    "content": [
      {
        "tool_use_id": "toolu_01VLAUQbgewcx9h7j6hYuynE",
        "type": "tool_result",
        "content": "1\t# Identify users - Docs\n2\t\n3\tLinking events to specific users enables you to build a full picture of how they're using your product across different sessions, devices, and platforms.\n4\t\n5\tThis is straightforward to do when [capturing backend events](/docs/product-analytics/capture-events?tab=Node.js.md), as you associate events to a specific user using a `distinct_id`, which is a required argument.\n6\t\n7\tHowever, in the frontend of a [web](/docs/libraries/js/features.md#capturing-events) or [mobile app](/docs/libraries/ios.md#capturing-events), a `distinct_id` is not a required argument — PostHog's SDKs will generate an anonymous `distinct_id` for you automatically and you can capture events anonymously, provided you use the appropriate [configuration](/docs/libraries/js/features.md#capturing-anonymous-events).\n8\t\n9\tTo link events to specific users, call `identify`:\n10\t\n11\tPostHog AI\n12\t\n13\t### Web\n14\t\n15\t```javascript\n16\tposthog.identify(\n17\t  'distinct_id',  // Replace 'distinct_id' with your user's unique identifier\n18\t  { email: 'max@hedgehogmail.com', name: 'Max Hedgehog' } // optional: set additional person properties\n19\t);\n20\t```\n21\t\n22\t### Android\n23\t\n24\t```kotlin\n25\tPostHog.identify(\n26\t    distinctId = distinctID, // Replace 'distinctID' with your user's unique identifier\n27\t    // optional: set additional person properties\n28\t    userProperties = mapOf(\n29\t        \"name\" to \"Max Hedgehog\",\n30\t        \"email\" to \"max@hedgehogmail.com\"\n31\t    )\n32\t)\n33\t```\n34\t\n35\t### iOS\n36\t\n37\t```swift\n38\tPostHogSDK.shared.identify(\"distinct_id\", // Replace \"distinct_id\" with your user's unique identifier\n39\t                           userProperties: [\"name\": \"Max Hedgehog\", \"email\": \"max@hedgehogmail.com\"]) // optional: set additional person properties\n40\t```\n41\t\n42\t### React Native\n43\t\n44\t```jsx\n45\tposthog.identify('distinct_id', { // Replace \"distinct_id\" with your user's unique identifier\n46\t    email: 'max@hedgehogmail.com', // optional: set additional person properties\n47\t    name: 'Max Hedgehog'\n48\t})\n49\t```\n50\t\n51\t### Dart\n52\t\n53\t```dart\n54\tawait Posthog().identify(\n55\t  userId: 'distinct_id', // Replace \"distinct_id\" with your user's unique identifier\n56\t  userProperties: {\n57\t    'email': 'max@hedgehogmail.com', // optional: set additional person properties\n58\t    'name': 'Max Hedgehog',\n59\t  },\n60\t);\n61\t```\n62\t\n63\tEvents captured after calling `identify` are identified events and this creates a person profile if one doesn't exist already.\n64\t\n65\tDue to the cost of processing them, anonymous events can be up to 4x cheaper than identified events, so it's recommended you only capture identified events when needed.\n66\t\n67\t## How identify works\n68\t\n69\tWhen a user starts browsing your website or app, PostHog automatically assigns them an **anonymous ID**, which is stored locally.\n70\t\n71\tProvided you've [configured persistence](/docs/libraries/js/persistence.md) to use cookies or `localStorage`, this enables us to track anonymous users – even across different sessions.\n72\t\n73\tBy calling `identify` with a `distinct_id` of your choice (usually the user's ID in your database, or their email), you link the anonymous ID and distinct ID together.\n74\t\n75\tThus, all past and future events made with that anonymous ID are now associated with the distinct ID.\n76\t\n77\tThis enables you to do things like associate events with a user from before they log in for the first time, or associate their events across different devices or platforms.\n78\t\n79\tUsing identify in the backend\n80\t\n81\tAlthough you can call `identify` using our backend SDKs, it is used most in frontends. This is because there is no concept of anonymous sessions in the backend SDKs, so calling `identify` only updates person profiles.\n82\t\n83\t## Best practices when using `identify`\n84\t\n85\t### 1\\. Call `identify` as soon as you're able to\n86\t\n87\tIn your frontend, you should call `identify` as soon as you're able to.\n88\t\n89\tTypically, this is every time your **app loads** for the first time, and directly after your **users log in**.\n90\t\n91\tThis ensures that events sent during your users' sessions are correctly associated with them.\n92\t\n93\tYou only need to call `identify` once per session, and you should avoid calling it multiple times unnecessarily.\n94\t\n95\tIf you call `identify` multiple times with the same data without reloading the page in between, PostHog will ignore the subsequent calls.\n96\t\n97\t### 2\\. Use unique strings for distinct IDs\n98\t\n99\tIf two users have the same distinct ID, their data is merged and they are considered one user in PostHog. Two common ways this can happen are:\n100\t\n101\t-   Your logic for generating IDs does not generate sufficiently strong IDs and you can end up with a clash where 2 users have the same ID.\n102\t-   There's a bug, typo, or mistake in your code leading to most or all users being identified with generic IDs like `null`, `true`, or `distinctId`.\n103\t\n104\tPostHog also has built-in protections to stop the most common distinct ID mistakes.\n105\t\n106\t### 3\\. Reset after logout\n107\t\n108\tIf a user logs out on your frontend, you should call `reset()` to unlink any future events made on that device with that user.\n109\t\n110\tThis is important if your users are sharing a computer, as otherwise all of those users are grouped together into a single user due to shared cookies between sessions.\n111\t\n112\t**We strongly recommend you call `reset` on logout even if you don't expect users to share a computer.**\n113\t\n114\tYou can do that like so:\n115\t\n116\tPostHog AI\n117\t\n118\t### Web\n119\t\n120\t```javascript\n121\tposthog.reset()\n122\t```\n123\t\n124\t### iOS\n125\t\n126\t```swift\n127\tPostHogSDK.shared.reset()\n128\t```\n129\t\n130\t### Android\n131\t\n132\t```kotlin\n133\tPostHog.reset()\n134\t```\n135\t\n136\t### React Native\n137\t\n138\t```jsx\n139\tposthog.reset()\n140\t```\n141\t\n142\t### Dart\n143\t\n144\t```dart\n145\tawait Posthog().reset();\n146\t```\n147\t\n148\tIf you *also* want to reset the `device_id` so that the device will be considered a new device in future events, you can pass `true` as an argument:\n149\t\n150\tWeb\n151\t\n152\tPostHog AI\n153\t\n154\t```javascript\n155\tposthog.reset(true)\n156\t```\n157\t\n158\t### 4\\. Person profiles and properties\n159\t\n160\tYou'll notice that one of the parameters in the `identify` method is a `properties` object.\n161\t\n162\tThis enables you to set [person properties](/docs/product-analytics/person-properties.md).\n163\t\n164\tWhenever possible, we recommend passing in all person properties you have available each time you call identify, as this ensures their person profile on PostHog is up to date.\n165\t\n166\tPerson properties can also be set being adding a `$set` property to a event `capture` call.\n167\t\n168\tSee our [person properties docs](/docs/product-analytics/person-properties.md) for more details on how to work with them and best practices.\n169\t\n170\t### 5\\. Use deep links between platforms\n171\t\n172\tWe recommend you call `identify` [as soon as you're able](#1-call-identify-as-soon-as-youre-able), typically when a user signs up or logs in.\n173\t\n174\tThis doesn't work if one or both platforms are unauthenticated. Some examples of such cases are:\n175\t\n176\t-   Onboarding and signup flows before authentication.\n177\t-   Unauthenticated web pages redirecting to authenticated mobile apps.\n178\t-   Authenticated web apps prompting an app download.\n179\t\n180\tIn these cases, you can use a [deep link](https://developer.android.com/training/app-links/deep-linking) on Android and [universal links](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/xcode/supporting-universal-links-in-your-app) on iOS to identify users.\n181\t\n182\t1.  Use `posthog.get_distinct_id()` to get the current distinct ID. Even if you cannot call identify because the user is unauthenticated, this will return an anonymous distinct ID generated by PostHog.\n183\t2.  Add the distinct ID to the deep link as query parameters, along with other properties like UTM parameters.\n184\t3.  When the user is redirected to the app, parse the deep link and handle the following cases:\n185\t\n186\t-   The mobile app is already authenticated. In this case, call [`posthog.alias()`](/docs/libraries/js/features.md#alias) with the distinct ID from the web. This associates the two distinct IDs as a single person.\n187\t-   The mobile app is unauthenticated. In this case, call [`posthog.identify()`](/docs/libraries/js/features.md#identifying-users) with the distinct ID from the web so pre-login mobile events stay connected to the web session. When the user later logs in on mobile, call `identify()` again with your canonical user ID.\n188\t\n189\tAs long as you associate the distinct IDs with `posthog.identify()` or `posthog.alias()`, you can track events generated across platforms.\n190\t\n191\tHere's an example implementation for handling deep links from web to mobile:\n192\t\n193\tPostHog AI\n194\t\n195\t### iOS\n196\t\n197\t```swift\n198\timport PostHog\n199\tclass DeepLinkIdentityManager {\n200\t    static let shared = DeepLinkIdentityManager()\n201\t    // MARK: - Deep Link Received\n202\t    func handleDeepLink(_ url: URL, isAuthenticatedOnMobile: Bool) {\n203\t        guard let webDistinctId = URLComponents(url: url, resolvingAgainstBaseURL: true)?\n204\t            .queryItems?.first(where: { $0.name == \"ph_distinct_id\" })?.value else {\n205\t            return\n206\t        }\n207\t        if isAuthenticatedOnMobile {\n208\t            // The mobile app already knows the current user.\n209\t            // Alias the incoming web distinct ID to that user.\n210\t            PostHogSDK.shared.alias(webDistinctId)\n211\t        } else {\n212\t            // Reuse the web distinct ID until login on mobile.\n213\t            PostHogSDK.shared.identify(webDistinctId)\n214\t        }\n215\t    }\n216\t    // MARK: - Login/Signup\n217\t    func handleLogin(canonicalUserId: String) {\n218\t        // Switch from the web distinct ID (or a mobile anon ID)\n219\t        // to your canonical user ID.\n220\t        PostHogSDK.shared.identify(canonicalUserId)\n221\t        // Set user properties, track signup event, etc.\n222\t    }\n223\t    func handleLogout() {\n224\t        PostHogSDK.shared.reset()\n225\t    }\n226\t}\n227\t```\n228\t\n229\t### Android\n230\t\n231\t```kotlin\n232\timport android.net.Uri\n233\timport com.posthog.PostHog\n234\tobject DeepLinkIdentityManager {\n235\t    // Deep Link Received\n236\t    fun handleDeepLink(uri: Uri, isAuthenticatedOnMobile: Boolean) {\n237\t        val webDistinctId = uri.getQueryParameter(\"ph_distinct_id\") ?: return\n238\t        if (isAuthenticatedOnMobile) {\n239\t            // The mobile app already knows the current user.\n240\t            // Alias the incoming web distinct ID to that user.\n241\t            PostHog.alias(webDistinctId)\n242\t        } else {\n243\t            // Reuse the web distinct ID until login on mobile.\n244\t            PostHog.identify(webDistinctId)\n245\t        }\n246\t    }\n247\t    // Login/Signup\n248\t    fun handleLogin(canonicalUserId: String) {\n249\t        // Switch from the web distinct ID (or a mobile anon ID)\n250\t        // to your canonical user ID.\n251\t        PostHog.identify(canonicalUserId)\n252\t        // Set user properties, track signup event, etc.\n253\t    }\n254\t    fun handleLogout() {\n255\t        PostHog.reset()\n256\t    }\n257\t}\n258\t```\n259\t\n260\t## Further reading\n261\t\n262\t-   [Identifying users docs](/docs/product-analytics/identify.md)\n263\t-   [How person processing works](/docs/how-posthog-works/ingestion-pipeline.md#2-person-processing)\n264\t-   [An introductory guide to identifying users in PostHog](/tutorials/identifying-users-guide.md)\n265\t\n266\t### Community questions\n267\t\n268\tAsk a question\n269\t\n270\t### Was this page useful?\n271\t\n272\tHelpfulCould be better"
